17 dollars may be collected and retained by cities for such
18 permits;
19 (5) Governing bodies of counties may issue special
20 permits for utility vehicles to be used on county roads
21 within the county by licensed drivers. Fees of fifteen
22 dollars may be collected and retained by the counties for
23 such permits;
24 (6) Municipalities may by resolution or ordinance
25 allow utility vehicle operation on streets or highways under
26 the governing body's jurisdiction. Any person operating a
27 utility vehicle pursuant to a municipal resolution or
28 ordinance shall maintain proof of financial responsibility
29 in accordance with section 303.160 or maintain any other
30 insurance policy providing equivalent liability coverage for
31 a utility vehicle] Any person may operate a utility vehicle,
32 as defined in section 301.010, upon streets and highways
33 where the posted speed limit is fifty-five miles per hour.
34 This subsection does not prohibit a utility vehicle from
35 crossing a road or street at an intersection where the road
36 or street being crossed has a posted speed limit of more
37 than fifty-five miles per hour.
38 2. Any person operating a utility vehicle shall
39 maintain proof of financial responsibility in accordance
40 with section 303.160 or maintain any other insurance policy
41 providing equivalent liability coverage for a utility
42 vehicle.
43 3. No person shall operate a utility vehicle within
44 any stream or river in this state, except that utility
45 vehicles may be operated within waterways which flow within
46 the boundaries of land which a utility vehicle operator
47 owns, or for agricultural purposes within the boundaries of
48 land which a utility vehicle operator owns or has permission

SB 1798 3
49 to be upon, or for the purpose of fording such stream or
50 river of this state at such road crossings as are customary
51 or part of the highway system. All law enforcement
52 officials or peace officers of this state and its political
53 subdivisions or department of conservation agents or
54 department of natural resources park rangers shall enforce
55 the provisions of this subsection within the geographic area
56 of their jurisdiction.
57 [3.] 4. A person operating a utility vehicle on a
58 highway [pursuant to an exception covered in this section]
59 shall have a valid operator's or chauffeur's license, except
60 that a handicapped person operating such vehicle [under
61 subdivision (3) of subsection 1 of this section] for short
62 distances occasionally only on this state's roads when
63 operated between the hours of sunrise and sunset, but shall
64 not be required to have passed an examination for the
65 operation of a motorcycle, and the vehicle shall be operated
66 at speeds of less than forty-five miles per hour.
67 [4.] 5. No persons shall operate a utility vehicle:
68 (1) In any careless way so as to endanger the person
69 or property of another; or
70 (2) While under the influence of alcohol or any
71 controlled substance.
72 [5.] 6. No operator of a utility vehicle shall carry a
73 passenger, except for agricultural purposes. The provisions
74 of this subsection shall not apply to any utility vehicle in
75 which the seat of such vehicle is designed to carry more
76 than one person.
77 [6.] 7. A violation of this section shall be a class C
78 misdemeanor. In addition to other legal remedies, the
79 attorney general or county prosecuting attorney may
80 institute a civil action in a court of competent

